{"id": "duc04-testb-32:25#77", "contents": "Antitrust experts say that the problem facing the Justice Department is that the courts have provided no clear definition of tying and no clear guidelines for determining when contracts are illegally exclusionary. Professor Lawrence White of New York University notes that the courts treat tying as an unusual practice when in fact it is ubiquitous. The outcome of the trial, scheduled to begin in U.S. District Court in Washington, is uncertain, but an almost certain appeal will leave to the Supreme Court the task of bringing legal order to 100 years of clashing antitrust doctrines."}
